title: For Sale:  Remington 700 5R Milspec Gen 2
postcontent: For sale is my Remington 700 5R Milspec Gen 2, that is about 1 year old at the most.  The barrel is an offshoot of the M24 program at Remington.  See the reviews on this gun as it has tested by a number of pros and has performed very well.  This is a fine shooting gun, as you can see in my reloading spreadsheet which i snapshotted and attached.  I have logged almost every range round through this gun while tracking group performance.  There's a ton of life left in it as 308s, in general, and the 5R, in particular, wear very well!  The only reason I am selling it now is a budget crunch.  I'll be replacing it in a few months when I get caught back up.  You gotta do what you gotta do.This gun is mostly stock, but I did have a bit done.  I was running a super heavy scope, so I had the gunsmith at AJI increase the scope base screws from 6-48 to the military size 8-40.  It won't limit your future sight options, just makes for a more secure hold.  I also had a local holster maker create a custom kydex riser.  It currently has 2 different hole settings for bench or prone, but you can either drill another hole as necessary or slot the holes to fit more faces.  It is comfortable and fits perfectly.  The final customization was adding a steel reinforced, bedded picatinny rail for a bipod mount.  Simply changing out the sling swivels for a picatinny rail leaves a really weak foundation in this type of stock.  This thing is rock solid and has performed without flaw.The snapshot I attached shows some of the better groups I've pulled out of this gun.  Of course, some were better than others, but that is a part of load development.  If you are a reloader, i'll be happy to share this data with you, so you have a great idea on where to start with your loads.The scope base in the picture does not go with this gun.  I am going to be moving it to another gun.  I'll leave the screwsI am asking $1000.  Here is how that works out for you based on current
